<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Keckiella antirrhinoides </i>is a drought deciduous shrub to 1.5 m with wand-like stems. Its yellow flowers are showy fragrant, and they are pollinated by hummingbirds (Freeman et al. 1984). Plants are cold tolerant to at least 0 °F. This species has the characteristics of both chaparral and coastal scrub species. It has a chaparrallike growth form (Weaver 1998) and dark green, somewhat thickened, non-hairy leaves, but these leaves are partially drought-deciduous. Little is known about the species’s life history. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Keckiella antirrhinoides </i>is a component of many chaparral and coastal sage types, and the alliance occupies transitional sites between chaparral and coastal scrub vegetation. In some cases, stands can closely mirror the environmental characteristics in the <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum-Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>association (J. Menke, pers. comm. 2005). Stands in San Diego and western Riverside Cos. often occur on concave slopes or on north-facing hills (Klein and Evens 2005), in sites ecologically related to the <i>Artemisia californica </i>alliance. The alliance appears to be restricted to the Peninsular Ranges of southern California and adjacent Baja California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
