    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bi). Stands have been sampled in the San Dieguito River drainage near Lake Hodges (Evens and San 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bk-l, Bn). Stands from western Riverside Co. (Gordon and White 1994, Klein and Evens 2005) and central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) characterize the alliance. Weaver (1998) noted that dense stands of the alliance occur in a fairly limited area, primarily on steep north-facing slopes within the San Luis Rey and San Dieguito river valleys, 32-40 km from the coast in San Diego Co.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The “cross-formation” ecological position of this alliance provides it as an excellent candidate for monitoring in a regional setting. Shifts in its abundance and geographic positions could be associated with shifts in management, human disturbance, fire characteristics, and climate. The species is an excellent native, drought-resistant garden plant used successfully in restoration of type-converted coastal scrub (Cione et al. 2002). Apparently, dense stands strongly dominated by <i>Keckiella antirrhinoides </i>are not good habitat for the California gnatcatcher (Weaver 1998). </div>
</div>

    

    

